The following background data on cholera in India were extracted from the
GIDEON software program:
Endemic or potentially endemic areas include Andhra Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh,
Madhya Pradesh, Assam, Delhi, Gujarata, Haryana, Karnatka, Kerala,
Maharashtra, Manipur, Punjab, Tamil Nadu, West Bengal. Assam and Manipur
were removed from the Infected Area list (WHO) as of February 1997. Gujurat
and Punjab states were removed in 1998.
Year Cases Fatal
1991 6,993 149
1992 6,911 55
1993 9,437 53
1994 4,973 32
1995 3,315 5
1996 4,425 35
1997 2,768 16
1998 186 0 (January through March)
Infection due to _V. cholerae_ O139 has been reported since 1992, and
predominated in 5 states as of 1993; 831 isolates of O139 were registered
in Delhi during 1993 (29% of all cholera isolates). Since August 1996, _V.
cholerae_ O139 has been the predominant strain in Calcutta. In Tamil Nadu,
_V. cholerae_ O139 accounted for 98% of isolates in 1992, and 11% in 1995.
--
Dr. Steve Berger
